						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/Participatory-approaches-in-ARD/Related-developments/Starving-and-penniless-Ethiopian-farmers-rue-biofuel-choice" title="Starving and penniless, Ethiopian farmers rue biofuel choice" alt="link">Starving and penniless, Ethiopian farmers rue biofuel choice</a></h2>

	
					<p>As impoverished and landlocked Ethiopia was choked by high oil prices, the government allocated more than 400,000 hectares (988,000 acres) for biofuel crops development as part of a national strategy enacted last year. Farmers say Global Energy Ethiopia, an American-Israeli subsidiary which initially acquired 2,700 hectares to grow castor beans -- a toxic plant whose seed provides castor oil, lured them with false claims of continuous harvests and financial incentives. But it has now been six months without a harvest and they haven't respected their promise to cover costs (Source: AFP, 04 November 2008). </p>
